k, based on extensive research in low-income districts of Lima, provides a sophisticated analysis of the relationship between a resurgent civil society and democratization.Exploring the complex interactions among urban popular movements, local government, political parties, and nongovernmental organizations (NGOs), Schönwälder shows that the democratic potential of these movements is genuine but that their influence has been limited. His balanced assessment credits their achievements while illuminating the sources of their failures, mainly a variety of institutional barriers and a persistent threat of manipulation and co-optation by stronger actors, especially political parties. His analysis helps us understand better why the left has so often failed to convert its considerable support at the grassroots into political successes at higher levels.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aDemocratizationxPeru. 0aDemocratizationzPeru. 0aLocal governmentxPeru. 0aLocal governmentzPeru. 0aNew LeftxPeru. 0aNew LeftzPeru. 0aSocial movementsxPeruxPeruxPeru. 0aSocial movementszPeru. 0aUrban poorxPolitical activityxPeru. 0aUrban poorxPolitical activityzPeru. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / NGOs (Non-Governmental Organizations).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271023793zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271023793423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271023793.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE 